songs.title: Katy Song

description.plain:
“Katy Song” from the eponymous Red House Painters album (often called Rollercoaster) is one of the emotional heights of the 1990s indie scene. Acclaimed as the the 162nd best song of the 1990s by Pitchfork, “Katy Song” is generally acknowledged as the Red House Painters' best stand-alone song.

The grief behind the song is so profound that critic Adam Brent Houghtaling considers it the 93rd saddest song ever.

songs.full_title: Japanese to English by Red House Painters
songs.title: Japanese to English

description.plain:
With sparkling sounding guitars and a simple and slow drum pattern, Mark Kozelek reflects on his past relationship with his Japanese girlfriend.

His biggest regret seems to be communicating with a language he does not understand, creating an awkward relationship where both people can’t seem to understand each other without a tool that of course, fails to truly communicate one’s feelings in an accurate way.

He is unable to cope with the fact that he has great love for his girlfriend but cannot truly love her in an intimate way because of this awkwardness in communicating, creating depressive thoughts due to a desire that, as long as he is unable to understand Japanese, will never be fulfilled.

The feeling that each of them felt together was real and memorable but fails to truly manifest into a fulfilling relationship.
